{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471515"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:48:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:48:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"372"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/372"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.19,0.05,0.59,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48933"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"363"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44026"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48933"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a history of passing scanty meconium for the first two days of life and no bowel movements since. His parents report increasing abdominal distension over the last 48 hours, associated with poor oral intake and several bile-stained vomits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe was born at term via spontaneous vaginal delivery following an uncomplicated pregnancy. He does not take any regular medications and has no significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 160/min, respiratory rate of 60/min, temperature 37.8\u00b0C, and SpO2 98% on room air. His abdomen is soft but distended. Rectal examination produces a gush of gas and liquid stool.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA plain abdominal X-ray shows gaseous distension with multiple air-fluid levels at various sections of the small and large bowel.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Volvulus neonatorum","Meconium ileus","Jejunal atresia","Hirschsprung disease","Duodenal atresia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms of \u003Cstrong\u003EHirschsprung disease\u003C/strong\u003E, including failure to pass meconium, abdominal distension, and bilious vomiting. Hirschsprung disease is characterised by an aganglionic bowel segment, most commonly in the rectosigmoid region. This aganglionic segment fails to relax, preventing the passage of meconium and leading to typical symptoms. On physical examination, Hirschsprung disease is classically associated with an explosive release of stools from the anus once the finger is removed after digital rectal examination, as seen in this case. The plain abdominal X-ray showing abdominal distension with air-fluid levels further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolvulus neonatorum\u003C/strong\u003E results from intestinal malrotation and leads to obstruction. Patients usually present within the first month of life with bilious vomiting. The meconium is often passed normally and abdominal examination may be initially normal, which is not consistent with this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeconium ileus\u003C/strong\u003E is often associated with cystic fibrosis and characterised by thick meconium that fails to pass. This leads to intestinal obstruction and presents with symptoms similar to Hirschsprung disease. However, abdominal X-ray typically shows an absence of air-fluid levels and a soap bubble appearance (due to mixing of meconium and air), which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJejunal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of small bowel atresia. Patients usually present within the first few hours after birth with bilious vomiting. Abdominal X-ray typically shows evidence of intestinal atresia with a triple bubble sign, which is not described in this patient\u0027s X-ray findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuodenal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E is another type of small bowel atresia. Like jejunal atresia, it typically presents early with bilious vomiting. Rarely, vomiting may be non-bilious if the atresia occurs proximal to the entry of the common bile duct in the duodenum. Abdominal X-ray typically shows a double bubble sign, which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Abdominal distension, together with the failure of passage of meconium in a neonate, should always raise the possibility of Hirschsprung disease.","Hirschsprung disease is characterised by an aganglionic bowel segment, most commonly in the rectosigmoid region.","Rectal examination in Hirschsprung disease typically produces an explosive release of stool and gas."],"references":["Prasad G, Aziz A. Abdominal Plain Radiograph in Neonatal Intestinal Obstruction. Journal of Neonatal Surgery. 2016;6(1):6.","Bhatnagar SN. Hirschsprung\u0027s Disease in Newborns. J Neonatal Surg. 2013 Jan 1;2(4):51. PMID: 26023471; PMCID: PMC4420299.","Arbizu R, Freiberg B, Rodriguez L. Lower Gastrointestinal Functional and Motility Disorders in Children. Pediatr Clin N Am 2021; 68:1255\u201371."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"372"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:39:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-19T14:39:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48933"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":